[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] In the field of compiler optimizations, **available expressions** is an analysis algorithm that determines for each point in the program the set of expressions that need not be recomputed.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] Those expressions are said to be *available* at such a point.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] To be available on a program point, the operands of the expression should not be modified on any path from the occurrence of that expression to the program point.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] The analysis is an example of a forward data flow analysis problem.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] A set of available expressions is maintained.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] Each statement is analysed to see whether it changes the operands of one or more available expressions.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] This yields sets of available expressions at the end of each basic block, known as the **outset** in data flow analysis terms.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] An expression is available at the start of a basic block if it is available at the end of each of the basic block's predecessors.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] This gives a set of equations in terms of available sets, which can be solved by an iterative algorithm.
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] Available expression analysis is used to do global common subexpression elimination (CSE).
[src:data-flow-analysis/available-expression] If an expression is available at a point, there is no need to re-evaluate it.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] A simple way to perform data-flow analysis of programs is to set up data-flow equations for each node of the control-flow graph and solve them by repeatedly calculating the output from the input locally at each node until the whole system stabilizes, i.e., it reaches a fixpoint.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The efficiency and precision of this process are significantly influenced by the design of the data-flow framework, including the direction of analysis (forward or backward), the domain of values, and the join operation used to merge information from multiple control paths.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This general approach, also known as *Kildall's method*, was developed by Gary Kildall while teaching at the Naval Postgraduate School.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Data-flow analysis is the process of collecting information about the way the variables are defined and used in the program.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It attempts to obtain particular information at each point in a procedure.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Usually, it is enough to obtain this information at the boundaries of basic blocks, since from that it is easy to compute the information at points in the basic block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In forward flow analysis, the exit state of a block is a function of the block's entry state.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This function is the composition of the effects of the statements in the block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The entry state of a block is a function of the exit states of its predecessors.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In this, $trans_{b}$ is the **transfer function** of the block b .
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It works on the entry state $in_{b}$ , yielding the exit state $out_{b}$ .
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The join operation $join$ combines the exit states of the predecessors $p\in pred_{b}$ of b , yielding the entry state of b .
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] After solving this set of equations, the entry and/or exit states of the blocks can be used to derive properties of the program at the block boundaries.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The transfer function of each statement separately can be applied to get information at a point inside a basic block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Each particular type of data-flow analysis has its own specific transfer function and join operation.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Some data-flow problems require backward flow analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This follows the same plan, except that the transfer function is applied to the exit state yielding the entry state, and the join operation works on the entry states of the successors to yield the exit state.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The entry point (in forward flow) plays an important role: Since it has no predecessors, its entry state is well defined at the start of the analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] For instance, the set of local variables with known values is empty.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If the control-flow graph does not contain cycles (there were no explicit or implicit loops in the procedure) solving the equations is straightforward.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The control-flow graph can then be topologically sorted; running in the order of this sort, the entry states can be computed at the start of each block, since all predecessors of that block have already been processed, so their exit states are available.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If the control-flow graph does contain cycles, a more advanced algorithm is required.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The most common way of solving the data-flow equations is by using an iterative algorithm.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It starts with an approximation of the in-state of each block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The out-states are then computed by applying the transfer functions on the in-states.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] From these, the in-states are updated by applying the join operations.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The latter two steps are repeated until we reach the so-called **fixpoint**: the situation in which the in-states (and the out-states in consequence) do not change.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] To be usable, the iterative approach should actually reach a fixpoint.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This can be guaranteed by imposing constraints on the combination of the value domain of the states, the transfer functions and the join operation.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The value domain should be a partial order with **finite height** (i.e., there are no infinite ascending chains $x_{1}$ < $x_{2}$ < ...).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The combination of the transfer function and the join operation should be monotonic with respect to this partial order.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Monotonicity ensures that on each iteration the value will either stay the same or will grow larger, while finite height ensures that it cannot grow indefinitely.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Thus we will ultimately reach a situation where T(x) = x for all x, which is the fixpoint.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It is easy to improve on the algorithm above by noticing that the in-state of a block will not change if the out-states of its predecessors don't change.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Therefore, we introduce a **work list**: a list of blocks that still need to be processed.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Whenever the out-state of a block changes, we add its successors to the work list.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In each iteration, a block is removed from the work list.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If the out-state changed, the block's successors are added to the work list.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] For efficiency, a block should not be in the work list more than once.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The algorithm is started by putting information-generating blocks in the work list.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It terminates when the work list is empty.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The efficiency of iteratively solving data-flow equations is influenced by the order at which local nodes are visited.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Furthermore, it depends on whether the data-flow equations are used for forward or backward data-flow analysis over the CFG.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Intuitively, in a forward flow problem, it would be fastest if all predecessors of a block have been processed before the block itself, since then the iteration will use the latest information.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In the absence of loops it is possible to order the blocks in such a way that the correct out-states are computed by processing each block only once.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In the following, a few iteration orders for solving data-flow equations are discussed (a related concept to iteration order of a CFG is tree traversal of a tree).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The initial value of the in-states is important to obtain correct and accurate results.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If the results are used for compiler optimizations, they should provide **conservative** information, i.e. when applying the information, the program should not change semantics.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The iteration of the fixpoint algorithm will take the values in the direction of the maximum element.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Initializing all blocks with the maximum element is therefore not useful.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] At least one block starts in a state with a value less than the maximum.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The details depend on the data-flow problem.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If the minimum element represents totally conservative information, the results can be used safely even during the data-flow iteration.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] If it represents the most accurate information, fixpoint should be reached before the results can be applied.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The following are examples of properties of computer programs that can be calculated by data-flow analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Note that the properties calculated by data-flow analysis are typically only approximations of the real properties.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This is because data-flow analysis operates on the syntactical structure of the CFG without simulating the exact control flow of the program.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] However, to be still useful in practice, a data-flow analysis algorithm is typically designed to calculate an upper respectively lower approximation of the real program properties.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The reaching definition analysis calculates for each program point the set of definitions that may potentially reach this program point.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The reaching definition of variable `a` at line 7 is the set of assignments `a = 5` at line 2 and `a = 3` at line 4.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The live variable analysis calculates for each program point the variables that may be potentially read afterwards before their next write update.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The result is typically used by dead code elimination to remove statements that assign to a variable whose value is not used afterwards.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The in-state of a block is the set of variables that are live at the start of it.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] It initially contains all variables live (contained) in the block, before the transfer function is applied and the actual contained values are computed.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The transfer function of a statement is applied by killing the variables that are written within this block (remove them from the set of live variables).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The out-state of a block is the set of variables that are live at the end of the block and is computed by the union of the block's successors' in-states.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The in-state of b3 only contains *b* and *d*, since *c* has been written.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The out-state of b1 is the union of the in-states of b2 and b3.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The definition of *c* in b2 can be removed, since *c* is not live immediately after the statement.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Solving the data-flow equations starts with initializing all in-states and out-states to the empty set.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The work list is initialized by inserting the exit point (b3) in the work list (typical for backward flow).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Its computed in-state differs from the previous one, so its predecessors b1 and b2 are inserted and the process continues.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The progress is summarized in the table below.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Note that b1 was entered in the list before b2, which forced processing b1 twice (b1 was re-entered as predecessor of b2).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Inserting b2 before b1 would have allowed earlier completion.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Initializing with the empty set is an optimistic initialization: all variables start out as dead.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Note that the out-states cannot shrink from one iteration to the next, although the out-state can be smaller than the in-state.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] This can be seen from the fact that after the first iteration the out-state can only change by a change of the in-state.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Since the in-state starts as the empty set, it can only grow in further iterations.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Several modern compilers use static single-assignment form as the method for analysis of variable dependencies.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] In 2002, Markus Mohnen described a new method of data-flow analysis that does not require the explicit construction of a data-flow graph, instead relying on abstract interpretation of the program and keeping a working set of program counters.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] At each conditional branch, both targets are added to the working set.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Each path is followed for as many instructions as possible (until end of program or until it has looped with no changes), and then removed from the set and the next program counter retrieved.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] A combination of control flow analysis and data flow analysis has shown to be useful and complementary in identifying cohesive source code regions implementing functionalities of a system (e.g., features, requirements or use cases).
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] There are a variety of special classes of dataflow problems which have efficient or general solutions.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The examples above are problems in which the data-flow value is a set, e.g. the set of reaching definitions (Using a bit for a definition position in the program), or the set of live variables.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] These sets can be represented efficiently as **bit vectors**, in which each bit represents set membership of one particular element.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Using this representation, the join and transfer functions can be implemented as bitwise logical operations.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The join operation is typically union or intersection, implemented by bitwise *logical or* and *logical and*.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The transfer function for each block can be decomposed in so-called *gen* and *kill* sets.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] As an example, in live-variable analysis, the join operation is union.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] The *kill* set is the set of variables that are written in a block, whereas the *gen* set is the set of variables that are read without being written first.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Dataflow problems which have sets of data-flow values which can be represented as bit vectors are called **bit vector problems**, **gen-kill problems**, or **locally separable problems**.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Such problems have generic polynomial-time solutions.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] There are several implementations of IFDS-based dataflow analyses for popular programming languages, e.g. in the Soot and WALA frameworks for Java analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Every bitvector problem is also an IFDS problem, but there are several significant IFDS problems that are not bitvector problems, including truly-live variables and possibly-uninitialized variables.
[src:data-flow-analysis/data-flow-analysis] Data-flow analysis is typically path-insensitive, though it is possible to define data-flow equations that yield a path-sensitive analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Within computer science, a **use-definition chain** (or **UD chain**) is a data structure that consists of a use *U*, of a variable, and all the definitions *D* of that variable that can reach that use without any other intervening definitions.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] A UD Chain generally means the assignment of some value to a variable.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] A counterpart of a *UD Chain* is a **definition-use chain** (or **DU chain**), which consists of a definition *D* of a variable and all the uses *U* reachable from that definition without any other intervening definitions.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Both UD and DU chains are created by using a form of static code analysis known as data flow analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Knowing the use-def and def-use chains for a program or subprogram is a prerequisite for many compiler optimizations, including constant propagation and common subexpression elimination.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Making the use-define or define-use chains is a step in liveness analysis, so that logical representations of all the variables can be identified and tracked through the code.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Notice that `x` is assigned a value at three points (marked A, B, and C).
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] However, at the point marked "1", the use-def chain for `x` should indicate that its current value must have come from line B (and its value at line B must have come from line A).
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Contrariwise, at the point marked "2", the use-def chain for `x` indicates that its current value must have come from line C.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] Since the value of the `x` in block 2 does not depend on any definitions in block 1 or earlier, `x` might as well be a different variable there; practically speaking, it *is* a different variable — call it `x2`.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] The process of splitting `x` into two separate variables is called live range splitting.
[src:data-flow-analysis/def-use-chain] The list of statements determines a strong order among statements.
