[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] In compilers, **live variable analysis** (or simply **liveness analysis**) is a classic data-flow analysis to calculate the variables that are *live* at each point in the program.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] A variable is *live* at some point if it holds a value that may be needed in the future, or equivalently if its value may be read before the next time the variable is written to.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The set of live variables between lines 2 and 3 is {`b`, `c`} because both are used in the multiplication on line 3.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] But the set of live variables after line 1 is only {`b`}, since variable `c` is updated later, on line 2.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The value of variable `a` is not used in this code.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] Note that the assignment to `a` may be eliminated as `a` is not used later, but there is insufficient information to justify removing all of line 3 as `f` may have side effects (printing `b * c`, perhaps).
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] Liveness analysis is a "backwards may" analysis.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The analysis is done in a backwards order, and the dataflow confluence operator is set union.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] This is in contrast to a "backwards must" analysis which would instead enforce this condition on all branches moving forward.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] : The set of variables that are used in s before any assignment in the same basic block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The in-state of a block is the set of variables that are live at the start of the block.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] Its out-state is the set of variables that are live at the end of it.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The out-state is the union of the in-states of the block's successors.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] The transfer function of a statement is applied by making the variables that are written dead, then making the variables that are read live.
[src:data-flow-analysis/live-variable-analysis] Solving the data flow equations starts with initializing all in-states and out-states to the empty set.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] In compiler theory, a **reaching definition** for a given instruction is an earlier instruction whose target variable can reach (be assigned to) the given one without an intervening assignment.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] `d1` is no longer a reaching definition for `d3`, because `d2` kills its reach: the value defined in `d1` is no longer available and cannot reach `d3`.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] The similarly named **reaching definitions** is a data-flow analysis which statically determines which definitions may reach a given point in the code.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] Because of its simplicity, it is often used as the canonical example of a data-flow analysis in textbooks.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] The data-flow confluence operator used is set union, and the analysis is forward flow.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] Reaching definitions are used to compute use-def chains.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] In other words, the set of reaching definitions going into S are all of the reaching definitions from S 's predecessors, $pred[S]$ . $pred[S]$ consists of all of the basic blocks that come before S in the control-flow graph.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] The reaching definitions coming out of S are all reaching definitions of its predecessors minus those reaching definitions whose variable is killed by S plus any new definitions generated within S .
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] where ${\rm {DEFS}}[y]$ is the set of all definitions that assign to the variable y .
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] Here d is a unique label attached to the assigning instruction; thus, the domain of values in reaching definitions are these instruction labels.
[src:data-flow-analysis/reaching-definition] Reaching definition is usually calculated using an iterative worklist algorithm.
